---
import GuideLayout from "../../layouts/GuideLayout.astro";

const title = "Azure NAT Gateway cost: why bills spike and how to model them";
const description =
  "A practical NAT Gateway estimate: hourly baseline + GB processed (plus egress). Includes common failure patterns that multiply outbound traffic.";

const faqs = [
  {
    q: "Why do NAT bills spike?",
    a: "Retry storms, large outbound downloads, container image pulls, and unbounded logging/telemetry can multiply GB processed quickly.",
  },
  {
    q: "How do I estimate quickly?",
    a: "Estimate baseline hours plus monthly GB outbound through NAT. Add a multiplier for retries/timeouts if the workload is not yet stable.",
  },
  {
    q: "How do I validate?",
    a: "Validate which subnets route through NAT and measure outbound GB from flow logs or a representative traffic window.",
  },
];
---
<GuideLayout title={title} description={description} canonicalPath="/guides/azure-nat-gateway-cost" lastUpdated="2026-01-22" faqs={faqs}>
  <p>
    NAT gateways are deceptively simple: an hourly baseline plus a data processing driver. The real problem is that NAT sits
    on the hot path for outbound traffic, so any retry storm or oversized download can amplify cost.
  </p>

  <h2>1) Baseline hours</h2>
  <p>Model NAT gateway count Ã— hours per month.</p>

  <h2>2) GB processed</h2>
  <p>
    The practical way to estimate GB processed is to list the major outbound flows routed via NAT: container pulls, package
    downloads, external API calls, telemetry, and backups. Then estimate monthly GB for each flow.
  </p>
  <p>
    Tool: <a href="/calculators/data-egress-cost-calculator/">Data egress cost calculator</a>.
  </p>

  <h2>3) Common cost multipliers</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Retries/timeouts to external APIs (each retry repeats full payload transfer).</li>
    <li>Image pulls during node churn or frequent redeploys.</li>
    <li>Uncached package downloads in CI or autoscaling environments.</li>
    <li>High-volume telemetry/log shipping routed through NAT.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Validation checklist</h2>
  <ul>
    <li>Validate which subnets and workloads egress via NAT (routing tables matter).</li>
    <li>Validate peak periods (deployments, incidents, scale-outs) where GB processed spikes.</li>
    <li>Validate that large downloads are cached (registry mirrors, package proxies, CDN).</li>
  </ul>

